Lawyer Willie Kimani and two other people he was abducted with died from fractures caused by a blunt object.A postmortem result has revealed that the trio's subsequent death was a result of being hit in the head.Kimani, 32, his client Josephat Mwenda and taxi driver Joseph Muiruri were killed and their bodies dumped in Oldonyo Sabuk river.According to the report, Kimani was beaten up several times at the back of his head by assailants before being strangled to death. When his body was found, he was still tied by a rope.On the other hand, the taxi driver was first strangled and then beaten on the head with the same blunt object.The results, released on Monday, indicated that Mwenda incurred severe bleeding on the neck, chest and a fracture on his head.The autopsy was carried out at Kenyatta National Hospital by government pathologist Johansen Oduor accompanied by other specialists.Police officers Fredrick Leliman, Stephen Chebulet and Silvia Wanjiku were later arrested and detained over the killings of the three. Read: Police officers linked to lawyer Kimani's murder in court, detained 14 daysWent missing after caseKimani and his client, Mwenda had filed a complaint alleging that Mwenda had been shot and injured by police in April.Mwenda was then charged with a range of offenses, including possessing drugs, gambling in public and resisting arrest, rights activists said.The two, as well as Muiruri, who went missing after a session at Mavoko law courts were found on Thursday last week.Shortly after the bodies were retrieved, LSK marched to the Inspector General's office to demand an investigation.On Monday, more than 30 local and international human rights groups and lawyers took to the streets over the killings.Activists demanded that government agencies begin investigations into the "heinous" deaths of the three.The Monday's countrywide demonstrations took place at Freedom Corner Nairobi, at the Mombasa law courts, the Jomo Kenyatta Sports Ground in Kisumu, and Railways Grounds Nakuru.Read: Jubilee politicians give Boinnet 7 days to arrest all cops in lawyer's deathThe activists asked IG Joseph Boinnet to clarify whether the AP officer accused of shooting Mwenda in April 2015 is one of those under arrest.Rights groups have in the past accused some sections of the police of involvement in extrajudicial killings, a charge that the security authorities have denied.